
[1]syncopy

   SYN'COPY, n. [Gr. to cut off.]

   1. In music, the same as syncopation; the division of a note introduced
   when two or more notes of one part answer to a single note of another.

   2. In grammar, an elision or retrenchment of one or more letters or a
   syllable from the middle of a word.

   3. In medicine, a fainting or swooning; a diminution or interruption of
   the motion of the heart, and of respiration, accompanied with a
   suspension of the action of the brain and a temporary loss of
   sensation, volition and other faculties.
